## What happened

In **.NET 11**, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (and any DSA signing/verification) now **throws at runtime** on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch the signing algorithm. Your options:

1. **Run DSA verification only on Linux/Windows.** Gate the code with a runtime check:
   ```csharp
   if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
       throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11+");
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** (e.g., [BouncyCastle](https://www.bouncycastle.org/csharp/)) that provides its own DSA implementation independent of the OS:
   ```csharp
   // Using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto for DSA verification
   var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   verifier.Init(false, publicKeyParam);
   verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Keep macOS on .NET 10** until the legacy signatures are phased out.

**Recommendation:** If you must verify existing DSA signatures on all three platforms, option **2** (BouncyCastle or similar) is the most practical path forward. Long-term, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** for new signatures.
